Only still ocean does not have any ripples or their movement. Simi=
larly only ummanifest atma (Self after dissolution/pralaya and before new s=
rishti/creation) does not have any objects and actions within it. Atma duri=
ng a srishti cycle does have many objects within it and many actions betwee=
n them.
=A0
Thus, realizing Self does NOT mean sitting still in a forest an=
d doing nothing. Various bodies keep doing various actions. A realized pers=
on identifies with atma and actions by various people seem to him/her like =
his/her actions. One does not particularly identify with what one's old bod=
y specifically does (based on previous momentum).
=A0
Nature uses such real=
ized people to set good examples for the world. So they do engage in some a=
ctions. They have no pride or shame, no happiness or sadness and do whateve=
r spontaneously occurs to them.
=A0
Shankara performing last rites for moth=
er would've made Mother happy. Moreover, it would set an example for future=
. One's interaction with the world is give & take. We give things to others=
 and take things from them. True renunciation is in renouncing what we take=
. There is no need to renounce giving. As the prevant notion of sannyasa wa=
s to cut off from the world, Shankara demonstrated giving others (e.g. moth=
er) sannyasa.
=A0
Swami Vivekananda and Swami Sivananda took this further. =
They engaged in a lot of service for the society, unlike other sannyasis wh=
o lock themselves in isolation.
=A0
Of course, if the act of "giving" incre=
ases pride (i.e. you are "taking" something in return of what you are givin=
g!!!), then a sannyasi better isolate oneself from the world and neither gi=
ve nor take (except absolute essentials for survival). But, when one progre=
sses beyond some level, it is a good idea to "give" what one is in a positi=
on to give others.
=A0
The purpose of life is to give and not to take, thou=
gh some taking is unavoidable in the process of giving. Focus on what you g=
ive and not on what you take.
